events.description: At Gresham College, twelve men, including Christopher Wren, Robert Boyle, John Wilkins, and Sir Robert Moray decide to found what is later known as the Royal Society.
events.html: • 1660 – At Gresham College, twelve men, including Christopher Wren, Robert Boyle, John Wilkins, and Sir Robert Moray decide to found what is later known as the Royal Society.

events.description: The first Treaty of Hopewell is signed, by which the United States acknowledges Cherokee lands in what is now East Tennessee.

events.description: Trade between the United States and modern-day Uruguay begins when John Leamy's frigate John arrives in Montevideo.
events.html: • 1798 – Trade between the United States and modern-day Uruguay begins when John Leamy's frigate John arrives in Montevideo.[7]

events.description: Beethoven's Piano Concerto No. 5 in E-flat major, Op. 73, premieres at the Gewandhaus in Leipzig.

events.description: The Times of London becomes the first newspaper to be produced on a steam-powered printing press, built by the German team of Koenig & Bauer.
events.html: • 1814 – The Times of London becomes the first newspaper to be produced on a steam-powered printing press, built by the German team of Koenig & Bauer.

events.description: Panama Independence Day: Panama separates from Spain and joins Gran Colombia.
events.html: • 1821 – Panama Independence Day: Panama separates from Spain and joins Gran Colombia.

events.html: • 1843 – Ka Lā Hui (Hawaiian Independence Day): The Kingdom of Hawaii is officially recognized by the United Kingdom and France as an independent nation.

events.description: American Civil War: The Confederate States of America accept a rival state government's pronouncement that declares Missouri to be the 12th state of the Confederacy.

events.description: American Civil War: In the Battle of Cane Hill, Union troops under General James G. Blunt defeat General John Marmaduke's Confederates.

events.description: Notts County F.C. is founded in Nottingham, England, making it the oldest professional Association football club in the world.
events.html: • 1862 – Notts County F.C. is founded in Nottingham, England, making it the oldest professional Association football club in the world.[8]

events.description: Bulgarian victory in the Serbo-Bulgarian War preserves the Unification of Bulgaria.
events.html: • 1885 – Bulgarian victory in the Serbo-Bulgarian War preserves the Unification of Bulgaria.

events.description: Women's suffrage in New Zealand concludes with the 1893 New Zealand general election.
events.html: • 1893 – Women's suffrage in New Zealand concludes with the 1893 New Zealand general election.

events.description: The first American automobile race takes place over the 54 miles from Chicago's Jackson Park to Evanston, Illinois. Frank Duryea wins in approximately 10 hours.
events.html: • 1895 – The first American automobile race takes place over the 54 miles from Chicago's Jackson Park to Evanston, Illinois. Frank Duryea wins in approximately 10 hours.

events.description: The Second Boer War: A British column is engaged by Boer forces at the Battle of Modder River; although the Boers withdraw, the British suffer heavy casualties.
events.html: • 1899 – The Second Boer War: A British column is engaged by Boer forces at the Battle of Modder River; although the Boers withdraw, the British suffer heavy casualties.

events.description: Irish nationalist Arthur Griffith founds Sinn Féin as a political party with the main aim of establishing a dual monarchy in Ireland.
events.html: • 1905 – Irish nationalist Arthur Griffith founds Sinn Féin as a political party with the main aim of establishing a dual monarchy in Ireland.

events.description: A mine explosion in Marianna, Pennsylvania, kills 154 men, leaving only one survivor.
events.html: • 1908 – A mine explosion in Marianna, Pennsylvania, kills 154 men, leaving only one survivor.

events.description: Albania declares its independence from the Ottoman Empire.
events.html: • 1912 – Albania declares its independence from the Ottoman Empire.

events.description: World War I: Following a war-induced closure in July, the New York Stock Exchange re-opens for bond trading.
events.html: • 1914 – World War I: Following a war-induced closure in July, the New York Stock Exchange re-opens for bond trading.

events.description: The Estonian Provincial Assembly declares itself the sovereign power of Estonia.

events.description: The Soviet Forces move against Estonia when the 6th Red Rifle Division strikes the border town of Narva, marking the beginning of the Estonian War of Independence.

events.description: FIDAC (The Interallied Federation of War Veterans Organisations), the first international organization of war veterans is established in Paris, France.

events.description: The Grand Ole Opry begins broadcasting in Nashville, Tennessee, as the WSM Barn Dance.

events.description: Chad, the Republic of the Congo, and Gabon become autonomous republics within the French Community.
